<DOC><DOCNO> ZF310-704-289 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 704 289.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDGE on andamp; about ATandamp;T  April 29, 1991 v6 n144 p9(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EDGE Publishing 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>SONET: Northern Telecom announces world's longest SONET route tospan 2,200 km in Western Canada. (Northern Telecom's S/DMSTransportNode used in the longest synchronous optical network inthe world)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Northern Telecom Ltd. (Services).andO;Ticker:    NT.andO;Product:   Northern Telecom S DMS TransportNode (Telecommunication switchingsystem) (Usage).andO;Topic:     SONET (Computer Network Protocol)Communications Service SuppliersTelecommunications ServicesOptical CommunicationsCanadaBroadbandCommunications Equipment.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Northern Telecom's S/DMS TransportNode transmission product has been selectedto form part of the longest synchronous optical network (SONET) route in theworld.andM;The contract, valued at $12 million, calls for the supply of Canada's firstinterprovincial long-haul SONET network.andP;  The contract was awarded by analliance of western telephone companies consisting of Manitoba TelephoneSystems, Saskatchewan Telephone and Alberta Government Telephones.andM;The high bandwidth network, part of the new Telecom Canada HDR2 (High-DensityRoute 2), will consist of more than 85 Northern Telecom S/DMS TransportNodes.andO;These SONET transmission systems will be located in 85 sites, span 2,200 km,and interconnect major metropolitan sites, including Edmonton, Calgary,Regina and Winnipeg.andM;&quot;This new route bears testament to Northern Telecom's FiberWorld vision of awideband, all fiber network for the high-speed telecommunications services ofthe 21st century,&quot; said Gedas A. Sakus, president, Northern Telecom Canada.andO;&quot;The ability of the S/DMS TransportNode to carry vast amounts of informationwill allow telephone companies to deliver increasingly sophisticated servicesto their customers.&quot;andM;Deliveries of the equipment will begin in mid-1991.andP;  The network will bephased into service by January 1992.andP;  The S/DMS TransportNode is manufacturedat Northern Telecom's facility in St. Laurent, Quebec, where a $60 millioninvestment in manufacturing and product development facilities was recentlycompleted.andM;Northern Telecom's FiberWorld vision is compatible with SONET standards,which have been established to optimize the capabilities of fiber-opticnetworks and provide higher bandwith and faster speeds for delivery ofadvanced telecommunications services.andM;The SONET network will switch high-speed data, text, image and full-motionvideo services as easily as it now switches voice signals.andM;With more than 200 systems now installed worldwide, the S/DMS TransportNodeOC-48 is the highest capacity SONET transport system in the world, operatingat 2.488 Gb/s.andO;</TEXT></DOC>